data.value: Dogs wag their tails as a form of communication, expressing a wide range of emotions and intentions. Primarily, tail wagging serves as a social signal, conveying feelings of happiness, excitement, or friendliness. When a dog greets someone they love or encounter a familiar scent, their wagging tail often signifies their joy and enthusiasm. However, tail wagging can also indicate other emotions, such as insecurity or apprehension, depending on the speed, height, and direction of the wag. Dogs may also wag their tails as a submissive gesture to express deference or as a warning sign when they feel threatened. In essence, tail wagging is a versatile language through which dogs convey their inner states and intentions to other dogs and to their human companions.
